 Abstract 
 
 Growth in farming depends on many things but one of the most important is investment in farming-based 
 research. Decision making in the farming-based research policy area can only be helped by access to better information. 
 This article summaries a recent try to move policy talk beyond only (not numbers-based) impressions towards a 
 process that is supported with new and clear data. The data used have been got together at ISNAR in a manner 
 designed to make comparisons both over time and between countries more valid than has been the case in the past. 
 The comparisons this way possible show/tell about large amounts of (many different kinds of people or things) both between countries and between broad (related to a large area) 
 groupings. Also lit up/educated here are issues related to the valuable thing (direction of pointing/way of thinking/information meeting), capital and labor strength, and 
 size and extent of particular national programs. 
 
 * Corresponding author. 
 The research data reported here are mostly from a study 
 begun/tried by ISNAR with help from the then Agnculture and (away from cities) Development Department of the World Bank 
 (Pardey, Roseboom and Anderson, 1991). The money-based values throughout this paper have been expressed in constant 
 1980 PPP dollars. PPP stands for buying-related power equality and 
 represents a (produced by people/not naturally-occurring) exchange rate that tries to reflect 
 the purchasmg power of a currency. Money-based values m 
 current local currency were first (lowered/flattened from losing air) to base-year 1980 
 with a local (GoP) deflator and then converted into constant 
 1980 dollars using 1980 PPP exchange rates taken from Summers and Heston (1988) and, for China, Summers and Heston 
 (1991). The authors thank Hugh Quigley for hts help in 
 preparing this paper. 
 
 Policy-makers are having to deal with unprecedently fast changes in the market for farming-based science and technology services. In the 
 less-developed countries, the fast (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) of 
 farming-based research ability (to hold or do something) experienced during 
 the 1960s and 1970s slowed much in the 
 1980s. Especially in debt-ridden areas, such as 
 sub-Saharan Africa, and Latin America and 
 Caribbean, investment in farming-based research 
 spoiled or even (lowered in number/got worse/gotten worse). Also, the level 
 of development aid to less-developed countries 
 stalled during the 1980s (OECD, 1989) while the 
 small but significant share that was channeled to 
 farming-based research is threatened by other demands. A reversal of these (popular things/general ways things are going) seems unlikely 
 
