 1. Public investments in national farming-based 
 research 
 
 1.1. Investment (popular things/general ways things are going) 
 
 Differences in patterns of farming-based growth 
 are in large part the result of national differences 
 in factor and (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) gifts and in 
 the policies put into use towards farming and, 
 more specifically, farming-based research. For two 
 20 years, up to the mid-1980s, worldwide  investment 
 in public farming-based research increased (in a big way). 1 Between 1961-65 and 1981-85, the total 
 number of (government) farming-based (people who work to find information) 
 grew at an average once-a-year rate of 4.2%. The 
 number of (people who work to find information) in less-developed countries increased by 7.2% a year, just over four 
 times the once-a-year rate in more-developed countries (Table 1). 
 In the period 1981-85, the less-developed 
 countries employed 59% of the world's farming-based (people who work to find information), compared with 33% in 1961-65. 
 Once-a-year growth rates in research investment in 
 less-developed countries have slowed during the 
 
