 1980s, most (in an obvious way) in sub-Saharan Africa, and 
 Latin America and Caribbean, both of which 
 have been struggling to contain flying/increasing international (money owed). In fact, the 1976-80 to 1981-85 
 once-a-year rate of growth in real research expenses was only 0. 7% for sub-Saharan Africa and 
 0.9% for Latin America and Caribbean compared 
 with a more-and less-developed country average 
 of 2.9% and 4.3%, (match up each pair of items in order). Although spending on farming-based research increased faster in 
 less-developed than in more-developed countries 
 during the past twenty years, the less-developed 
 countries' share of total expense on research 
 rose only to 48% from its 37% in 1961-65. 
 Of the less-developed areas, only in Asia and 
 Pacific did once-a-year growth in research expenses go beyond the once-a-year increase in (people who work to find information). 
 In more-developed countries, on the other hand, 
 spending on research increased twice as fast as 
 the number of (people who work to find information). 
 1.2. Expenses per (person who works to find information) 
 
 Average spending per (person who works to find information) in less-developed countries has been falling since the early 
 1970s. In 1981-85, it was actually lower in real 
 terms than in 1961-65. In more-developed countries meanwhile, spending per (person who works to find information) has been 
 rising steadily and the focus has regularly 
 been towards greater investment in workers within the NARSs. 
 One reason for the (compared to other things) lower spending 
 per (person who works to find information) in less-developed countries is that, 
 of late, the quickly expanded university systems in 
 these countries have produced many more graduates than (before that/before now). Many governments in lessdeveloped countries insist that public bodies, including research systems, employ graduates, but 
 then do not provide (good) enough matching money. 
 In the Asia and Pacific area, expense per 
 (person who works to find information) has always been lower than in other 
 less-developed areas. This is partly because relative prices for labor are lower, which causes a 
 substitution of labor for other inputs in the system. But it is also because they are ruled by 
 larger research systems that may well be able to 
 (understand/make real/achieve) (making a lot of an item so each item costs less) and range. 
 
