 In sub-Saharan Africa, expense per (person who works to find information) has for a long time been higher than in 
 other areas. During the 1960s, the NARSs in 
 this area continued to be heavily staffed by 
 expensive (ban from a country)s from the former 
 colonial powers. The poor quality of Africa's (set of machines) and the need to import nearly all 
 equipment also drive up the research costs in this 
 area. Although still higher than in most other 
 less-developed areas, spending per (person who works to find information) 
 in sub-Saharan Africa is falling, in part a reflection of the fact that (ban from a country) (people who work to find information) are 
 more and more being replaced by less expensive national research staff, and in part because of the 
 (talked about before this) money-related problems. 
 
 1.3. Workers 
 One of the basic strengths (or, too often, weaknesses) of NARSs, and a major factor in 
 deciding/figuring out the success of farming-based research, 
 lies in the quality, composition and use/military service 
 of their research staff. 
 Developing meaningful measures of this workers part is challenging both mentally and practically. Indicators such as university qualifications and years of research experience may explain much of the difference in 
 quality between research systems, but they are 
 not the only factors. The (combination of different substances, objects, people, etc.) of the 
 research staff will depend, among other things, 
 on the NARS's size and the type of research it is 
 conducting. These influences change/differ  greatly between areas and will change within a system 
 over time. For instance, a smaller NARS whose 
 activities are focused more on (taking by force)/(taking control of) research 
 spillovers and adapting them to local facts or conditions (that surround someone) is unlikely to need a group of (people who work to find information) 
 almost the same as  that needed/demanded by a large NARS that is 
 likely to argue with an completely different scale 
 and set of research problems. (in almost the same way), while a 
 system ruled by (people who work to find information) holding PhDs 
 and 20 years of experience may be thought about/believed 
 highly qualified, it is not necessarily the most 
 appropriate labor force to argue with the applied 
 and site-clearly stated/particular problems that face many national research systems today. 
