 is guessed to be around 3%. 
 Although money-based development can be expected to increase the supply of university graduates, research systems in some of the richer 
 less-developed countries appear to have difficulty 
 recruiting or keeping/holding qualified staff. In part, this 
 is because (moneys paid for working) and conditions in public farming-based research starts are not competitive 
 with other employment opportunities. In some countries, for example, universities employ 
 large numbers of PhDs in the farming-based sciences, while the national public farming-based research institutes employ few or none. 
 On the other hand, as argued earlier, a large 
 proportion of PhDs on the research staff does not 
