 ticularly when such training may be of (possibly not true, good, or honest) relevance. 
 1.4. Valuable thing orientation 
 In less-developed countries, farming-based research is directed mostly at crops. Based 
 on a sample of 83 countries, roughly two-thirds of 
 all farming-based (people who work to find information) are involved in work 
 related to crops. For the rest, 19% are 
 working at animals research, 7% in forestry research, and 6% in fisheries research. 
 There are some limited (related to a large area) weird differences in 
 the share of useful things/valuable supplies gave/reserved to a particular 
 valuable thing (direction of pointing/way of thinking/information meeting) (Table 3). While such weird differences are unavoidable, given (related to a large area) differences/different versions in 
 the pattern of production, it has been argued by 
 some that less research is loyal to/is dedicated to fisheries and 
 forestry than their reported money-based importance 
 warrants (see Mergen et a!., 1988, on forestry 
 research). In fact, the data - as shown in Table 3 
 - do not generally support this suggestion/possible plan. Research into forestry attracts more useful things/valuable supplies than 
 its matching share in farming-based output in all 
 areas. In Asia and Pacific, and West Asia and 
 North Africa, this is also true of fisheries. 
 Anyway, the actual facilities for research 
 into forestry and fisheries are limited, mostly 
 because NARSs in less-developed countries are 
 generally small. The majority (73%) of them employ fewer than 200 (people who work to find information) in total, while 
 only small percentages of these are involved in 
 research into fisheries or forestry. 
 
