 1.5. Factor shares 
 
 A major challenge for managers of research 
 systems is to make the most effective use of 
 available useful things/valuable supplies. The best mix of spending on 
 capital equipment, personnel and operating costs 
 will depend mostly on the relative 
 availability and cost of research inputs, their quality, and the type of research being managed and did/done. 
 Since the most effective combination will differ 
 between areas and change within a system over 
 time, it is silly to propose standards for 
 deciding/figuring out the 'optimal' mix of inputs in research. The data presented in this section should 
 be thought of as indications of importance based on 
 a sample of countries, not as money-based optima 
 necessarily to be targeted. 
 The available data suggest that, in 1981-85, 
 NARSs in less-developed countries on average 
 gave/reserved 19% of once-a-year expenses to capital 
 investment, compared with 8% in the U.S. The 
 higher share of spending on capital equipment by 
 NARSs in less-developed countries supports the 
 end/end result, also proven true by their fast growth, 
 that most are in an expansion-related phase. During 
 this phase, not only must capital stock be replaced but added/more capital stock must be gotten. The pattern of expenses in the U.S., 
 on the other hand, reflects that of a mature 
 system, most of whose capital spending involves 
 replacement of existing equipment. The focus 
 in the U.S. system has, more than that, been regularly towards greater investment in workers rather than physical capital over the last few years. 
 Today the system (does/completes) with around 14 cents 
 of physical capital for each dollar of workers, compared with about 27 cents 50 years ago 
 (Pardey, Eveleens and Hallaway, honest/appearing soon). 
 The modern pattern of expense in 
 less-developed countries mirrors that of U.S. experiment stations in their early years at the turn 
 of this century, when the share of capital in total 
 expenses rose steadily to peak at 29% in 
 1912, before steadily falling. Capital (i.e., land, 
 buildings, equipment, etc.) has claimed the same 
 share of overall spending in U.S. research stations (about 8%) for the past thirty years. 
 A second factor in the higher share of capital 
 
 costs in less-developed country NARSs is that 
 capital items are often (compared to other things) more expensive 
 in less-developed countries and they often lack 
 (good) enough repair and maintenance facilities, leading to an early write-off of equipment. Factor 
 substitution, where less expensive inputs are substituted for more expensive, may even out 
 this effect somewhat, but it is not likely that it 
 will outweigh it. 
 Whereas (moneys paid for working) and operating costs in farming-based research expenses represent service 
 flows, capital expenses represent additions to 
 a stock. So, the high share of capital in once-a-year 
 spending may also (state that something is much bigger, worse, etc., than it really is) the actual share of 
 capital in the services used to (do/complete) research. 
 Capital equipment can last for many years, and a 
 measure of service flow, rather than of expense, would probably reduce the share of capital 
 actually used by a research system in any given 
 year, especially if such a system expands quickly. 
 The repeating costs of NARSs can be divided 
 between (moneys paid for working) and operating costs. In less-developed countries, (moneys paid for working) tend to be lower and 
 operating costs higher than in more-developed 
 countries. In 1981-85, a sample of 43 less-developed countries spent an average of $48,100 in 
 constant 1980 dollars per (person who works to find information), compared 
 with $91,200 per (person who works to find information) in the U.S. The modern level of spending per (person who works to find information) in 
 less-developed countries again appears to reflect 
 the situation in the early years of the U.S. experiment stations. In fact, in the U.S., total spending 
 per (person who works to find information) fell steadily in the early years as 
 the (putting something into use) of (people who work to find information) ran faster than rises in 
 research expenses. In the first 30 years, real 
 operating expenses per (person who works to find information) fell to 
 roughly one-third of original levels and did not 
 recover until the 1970s - some 60 years later! 
 One of the major (problems, delays, etc.) in making reasonable cross-country comparisons of factor shares is 
 that cross-country differences in price levels, 
 which are not the same across different expense items, act to confuse the comparisons. 
 So, if spending on operating costs and (moneys paid for working) 
 is (changed to make better/changed to fit new conditions) to take account of price differences 
 between countries, research in less-developed 
 countries is seen to be more labor-intensive relative to the U.S. Looked at this way, the share of 
 
 J.R. Anderson eta!. I Farming-based Money flow 10 (1994) 107-123 
 
 operating costs in repeating expenses in 
 1981-85 averaged 15% in less-developed countries. 
 After (changing to make better/changing to fit new conditions) for cross-country price differentials, operating expenses per (person who works to find information) are 
 also much smaller in less-developed areas than 
 in the U.S. Farming-based (people who work to find information) in subSaharan Africa, Asia and Pacific, Latin America 
 and Caribbean, and West Asia and North Africa 
 work with only 50%, 43%, 74% and 22%, (match up each pair of items in order), of the operating useful things/valuable supplies gave/given to a 
 U.S. (person who works to find information). However, the (money paid for working) part 
 of repeating expenses (including the (moneys paid for working) 
 of both scientific and support staff) in the less-developed areas is much closer to the U.S. level. 
 And in sub-Saharan Africa it is even higher. This 
 may be accounted for by the (compared to other things) high number of (ban from a country)s still working in African NARSs 
 and the fact that the employment policies of 
 many governments in less-developed countries result in NARSs employing large numbers of support staff. 
 1.6. Size, scope, and spillovers 
 
 Since 1961-65, the average size of NARSs has 
 more than doubled, from around 400 to 910 (people who work to find information), as has average expense per system. 
 In less-developed countries the average size of 
 NARSs has increased from 155 to 630 full-time 
 equal (people who work to find information). Anyway, 95 of the 
 carefully thought about/believed 130 NARSs in less-developed countries still employ fewer than 200 (people who work to find information), while 
 39 systems employ fewer than 25 (people who work to find information). 
 Only 14 employ more than 1000, illustrating that 
 the growth and development of NARSs in the 
 past twenty years has separated significantly. 
 When carefully studying the cost structures and effectiveness of a NARS, one needs to think about  both 
 the overall size and (many different kinds of people or things) of its operations and 
 the farming-based system it serves. 
 The (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) on whether or not research operations are subject to (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) of size is limited 
 and far from definite. In the case of a NARS, 
 (things to carefully think about) of (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) of size are confused by the fact that these systems create a 
 wide (many different kinds of people or things) of products and services that change/differ 
 in their valuable thing, technology, and agroecologi- 
 
 113 
 
 cal level of detail. For example, certain activities can 
 relate to improving crops or to developing new 
 breeds of plants good for clearly stated/particular agroecological zones within a country. Or, research 
 can be loyal to/be dedicated to developing improved crop and 
 soil management practices that will allow farmers 
 across a range of agroecological zones to increase 
 yields or improve pest and disease control. 
 Even without size (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) with 
 regard to any particular line of research (e.g., a 
 particular valuable thing research program), a system may well be able to create (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) of 
 scope through a wise choice in its (mix of stocks, bonds, etc./document collection) 
 of research activities. Such scope (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) arise 
 when a system can begin/try a whole range of 
 research efforts/tries more cheaply than if these 
 efforts/tries were done/tried by separate research 
 things/businesses. These (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) can be (accomplished or gained), for 
 example, by sharing staff, equipment, information, or know-how between different lines of research. 
 An important hint/result/effect is that, when a system can create (good or well enough) strong (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) of 
 scope, these can, in turn, lead to (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) of 
 size across the whole range of its activities, even 
 if such (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) of size do not arise for some 
 individual research programs (Baumol, Panzar 
 and Willig, 1988). Of course, there can also arise 
 diseconomies of scope, especially among small 
 systems that spread their (not having enough workers, money, time, etc.) across 
 many research areas. So, small NARSs 
 will be unable to manage and do research in all areas 
