 I. 7. Research and working well 
 
 Research is best seen as an investment activity. 
 The research process itself takes time, and a 
 further period goes by before the results of research are taken up. Recent (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) suggests, 
 what's more, that the benefits of research can 
 
 still have an effect in increasing output for as 
 long as 30 years after the research was started. 
 To think about  gains in farming-based gross domestic 
 product (AgGDP) as a measure of the hit/effect of 
 (happening at the same time) research expense could 
 this way be sneaky and false. Differences in the quality of 
 land and labor, and in the strength of use of 
 other inputs such as (material that makes plants grow better)s and machinery, 
 will influence output and so distort international 
 comparisons of output that are measured only in 
 terms of research. 
 In fact, all the more- and less-developed areas steadily increased their research strengths 
 during that period (Table 4). In 1981-85, less-developed countries spent an average of nearly $4 
 per farming-based worker on research, 2.5 times the 
 amount spent twenty years before. In more-developed countries, spending on research increased 
 4.4 times over the same period, to $214 for every 
 farming-based worker. 
