 2. International investments in farming-based 
 research 
 
 Opposite to the situation in many areas of 
 scientific research, there has always been an important element of international cooperation in 
 farming-based research. Much of this is due to the 
 (future thing) of the colonial relationships that existed at 
 the time (put into a hospital)/(made a behavior acceptable) farming-based research 
 was developing. 
 One of the leading international organizations 
 in the field is the Advice-giving Group on International Farming-based Research (CGIAR), an umbrella body of around 40 donor countries and 
 international (services businesses/government units) that help develop the activities of 
 some dozen supranational research centers. ((not very long ago) the number was enlarged to 18 but our 
 discussion here refers to the original 13.) Ten of 
 these centers have their headquarters in less-developed countries. Most are involved in research 
 into either food valuable things or farming-based production problems in a particular (related to areas near the Equator/hot and humid) area, 
 and three begin/try worldwide research into clearly stated/particular valuable things. 
 Established in 1971, the stated goal of the 
 CGIAR (CG for short), was to help efforts to 
 increase food production in the less-developed 
 world. The goals were extended in 1990, in recognition of agriculture's wider role in money-based 
 development, to helping less-developed countries 
 (accomplish or gain with effort) dependability in food. Self-reliance is taken 
 to mean the ability (to hold or do something) of a country to provide 
 (good) enough food for its population, either directly 
 through local food production or indirectly by 
 creating farming-based exports that will allow food 
 to be imported. 
 In 1981-85, the CG accounted for only 1.8% 
 of worldwide  (government) spending on farming-based 
 
 115 
 
 research, 4.3% if related to spending by and for 
 less-developed countries. Its budget rose, in (in name only/very small amount) terms, from $20 million added/gave by 20 
 (people who give money or other things) in 1971, to $280 million from 40 (people who give money or other things) in 
 1990. If corrected for inflation, the CG expenses show clearly different phases of growth: 
 fast (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) during the 1970s, slower growth 
 during the 1980s, and seen/obvious spoiling or 
 even (lower in number/get worse) in the past few years. 
 The U.S. was the largest single donor to the 
 CG, although both Europe and Japan increased 
 their share of (things that are given/work that's done) during the 1980s. The 
 World Bank acted as a balancing "donor of last 
 resort," giving-out its money after other donor 
 plans were known. It lately has added/has given 
 around 15% of the system's total budget each 
 year. 
 During the 1980s, although the CG was established partly in response to the high levels of 
 poorness and hunger in Asia, the focus in the 
 portion of money has moved/changed to sub-Saharan 
 Africa. Between 1986 and 1988, sub-Saharan 
 Africa accounted for 39% of the CG's core expenses, compared with 26% to Asia, 21% to 
 Latin America and Caribbean, and 14% to West 
 Asia and North Africa. 
 The "appropriate" (related to a large area) portion of money 
 is just one of the policy issues facing the CG. 
 Although much of the increase in money/giving money (to) to 
 sub-Saharan Africa has been for special projects, 
 it is (able to be argued over) that the concentration of useful things/valuable supplies 
 has swung too much towards that area at the 
 final/best expense of Asia, which has a few-fold 
 more poor than sub-Saharan Africa. 
 The valuable thing (direction of pointing) of the system has 
 been subject to change over time. As the system 
 expanded, the share gave out to cereals research 
 declined steadily to about 40%, of which rice 
 research still accounts for the largest share at 
 17% of the system's total. Food crops, such as 
 potatoes, other roots and tubers, and (peas, beans, lentils, etc.), 
 account for 24% of the total, while animals 
 research accounts for around 20%. The remaining useful things/valuable supplies are set apart and given out to noncommodity programs, including farming systems, food policy, 
 (related to tiny chemical assembly instructions inside of living things) useful things/valuable supplies, and NARS ability (to hold or do something) building. 
 The recent (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) of the system has broadened the valuable thing coverage to include fish- 
 
 116 
 
 l.R. Anderson eta!./ Farming-based Money flow 10 (1994) 107-123 
 
 eries, agroforestry and forestry, and bananas and 
 plantains. It may also eventually include (plant-related) valuable things. 
 The recent readjustation of CG goals to 
 focus on dependability instead of independence 
 in food was a recognition of the fact that increasing food production is not, in itself, a solution to 
 the hunger problem. Future policies must reflect 
 the role of farming-based growth as a means of 
 creating added/more on-farm and off-farm income and employment, and the need to sustain 
 the natural-useful thing/valuable supply base on which continued 
 gains in farming-based working well depend. 
 The CG's first efforts were mostly targeted 
 toward more good production (surrounding conditions). 
 Technology packages were developed that involved higher rates of (material that makes plants grow better) (online or paper form that asks for a job, money, admission, etc.), improved water management and cultural practices, 
 along with new crop cultivars that were especially (able to reply or react/quick to respond) to more stronger production 
 governments. While the dramatic (thing that's given/work that's done) of these 
 technology packages to increasing worldwide  food 
 supplies is unquestioned (Anderson, Herdt and 
 Scobie, 1988), by the mid-1970s the CG had also 
 begun to address production restrictions in the 
 more not important (surrounding conditions) of the semi-dry and 
 (sub-)humid tropics. 
 Now, about 30% of CG money/giving money (to) is targeted towards technology for not important lands, 
 which is roughly equal to the percentage of the 
 poor population in less-developed countries that 
 live in these areas. The issue of the relative 
 good qualities of trying to improve or maintain working well of good against/compared to/or not important lands will continue to be an important one for the CG, especially with respect to the possible opportunity 
 costs (in terms of working well gains previous/unavoidable) of 
 diverting rare/not enough  research useful things/valuable supplies away from 
 more (able to reply or react/quick to respond) areas towards the more not important 
 ones. Analyses of the type reported by Byerlee 
 and Morris (1993) will be needed for guiding 
 future investment policy this way. 
 Research on useful thing/valuable supply management will become more important as the need for continued 
 increases in food production places an ever 
 greater strain on the world's valuable things from nature. 
 The CG has taken the first step in this direction. 
 Plans on how best to include agroforestry 
 
 and useful thing/valuable supply management concerns into its research program are now being put into use. 
 This is being done by expanding the system and 
 redesigning its approach in order to incorporate 
 institutional things/businesses that specifically face/deal with research concerns within an agroecological (way of seeing things / sensible view of what is and is not important). Aware of the fact that (how money affects people's lives) - not 
 just natural - conditions hold back the effectiveness and spillover (possible power or ability within/possibility of)  the system's research, this agroecological aspect is being overlaid on a (related to how land, rivers, etc. affect a country's rules and relationships) or (related to a large area) dimension to 
 create a (what people commonly call a/not really a) "(large area of land)al" (way of seeing things / sensible view of what is and is not important) 
 (TAC/ Center Directors Working Group, 1993). 
 
 3. Private investments in farming-based research 
 
 Any creation of future (government) research policy must take into account the level of 
 activity and changing role of the (people and businesses that are not part of the government) in 
 farming-based research. As farmers use more (bought) inputs and the value-added in farming 
 more and more moves off-farm to the marketing and 
